  "prompt": "Which one is grammatically correct: pick up someone at the airport or from the airport?",
  "response": "Both \"pick up someone at the airport\" and \"pick up someone from the airport\" are grammatically correct and commonly used, but they can have slightly different nuances depending on the context.\n\n1. **Pick up someone at the airport**: This phrase emphasizes the location where the action takes place. It means you are meeting someone physically at the airport premises.\n   - Example: \"I\u2019ll pick you up at the airport at 3 p.m.\"\n\n2. **Pick up someone from the airport**: This phrase emphasizes the origin or starting point of the journey. It implies that the person is coming from the airport.\n   - Example: \"I\u2019ll pick you up from the airport and drive you home.\"\n\nIn many cases, both can be used interchangeably without causing confusion. Choose the one that feels more natural in your sentence or context.",
